The Trojan horse of Europe.
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be allocated.
Emergency measures will have to be conditional.
The Greek government will have to make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to serve its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be insurmountable, but there will be future issues.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was having allowed Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was already clear that the country was not ready.
Her budget policy was already out of control when she joined the monetary union in 2001, and her unions were already pressing for Greek salaries to align with those practiced in Europe, despite a productivity lag.
But this response is too simplistic, in that such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a unemployment rate of 20% and astronomical budget deficits, sees Greece as a reflection of its own future.
But if that's not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy do a bit better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot proceed with a devaluation of their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek help.
Was the true error not in creating the euro?
As one of the few Americans who initially encouraged the idea of a European currency, you would be right to ask: am I reconsidering my initial position?
My response is no, creating the euro was not a mistake, but it could yet become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway down the path to a viable monetary union.
If she does nothing, the next crisis could well be a stroll in the park compared to this one.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, EU members can only lend aid to Greece by going beyond the regulation that bars them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond a country's control.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders offer their aid, public opinion and the markets tend to question their integrity.
If the problems stem from the Treaty of Lisbon, then it must be amended.
Moreover, aid should not be granted solely on certain conditions, but rather accompanied by temporary national budget control by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
History shows that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries subject to such measures will express their indignation.
But no one forces them to accept the money.
Moral considerations?
Here is the translated sentence:
Note that this would be a more effective mechanism of discipline than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
How would Californians react if their state temporarily handed its budget over to an expert appointed specifically by President Barack Obama's administration ?
It wouldn't bother them that much.
The expert would not be of California origin, but American.
The public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the California state as well as that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from where the orders of this expert would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans don't do things like this because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereign prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe truly wants to achieve its monetary union, it must overcome its past.
This union involves not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will truly have to answer to someone.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The German Chancellor Angela Merkel's electorate hates this kind of rescue because they know who will ultimately be responsible.
The Germans are opposed to anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not accountable, but today it has adopted an excessively monetary policy, thus critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The enormous current surpluses of Germany are thus worsening their situation even more.
Its budgetary stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has consequently benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should return the favor.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency lending facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She must provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she in the best position to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe to more effective political integration.
One can only hope.
